{
  "doc_id": "42605",
  "text": "Shigellosis is one of the main agents of diarrheal infections in developing countries especially among children <5 years of age. Shigella spp. isolates are the causative agents of 5-15% of all diarrheal infections worldwide 1 that have involved approximately 80-165 million cases, with over 600,000 deaths occurring each year. [CITATION_1] The infection dose of Shigella spp. is as low as 10-100 organisms and over 80% of infections are due to person-to-person transmission. [CITATION_2] Shigellosis infection is associated with the colonization of four Shigella spp. -S. dysenteriae, S. flexneri, S. boydii and S. sonnei -that among them S. flexneri and S. sonnei are frequently isolated from Iran [CITATION_3] and other developing countries. [CITATION_4] Many reports have also demonstrated a relatively high prevalence of shigellosis among children with diarrheal infections.",
